@article{webb2020,
  title = {{Divisive normalization does influence decisions with multiple alternatives.}},
  author = {Webb, R. and Glimcher, P. and Louie, K.},
  year = {2020},
  journal = {Nature Human Behaviour},
  publisher = {Nature Publishing Group},
  volume = {4},
  number = {11},
  pages = {1118-1120},
  doi = {10.1038/S41562-020-00941-5},
  abstract = {1Rotman School of Management, University of Toronto, Toronto, Ontario, Canada. 2Department of Economics, University of Toronto, Toronto, Ontario, Canada. 3Center for Neural Science, New York University, New York, NY, USA. 4Neuroscience Institute, New York University School of Medicine, New York, NY, USA. ✉e-mail: klouie@cns.nyu.edu Divisive normalization, an algorithm prominent in sensory processing and viewed as a canonical neural computation1, has recently been proposed to play a similarly important role in decision-making, capturing aspects of both neural value coding and choice behaviour2–13. In a previous study, divisive normalization was proposed to explain context-dependent independence from irrelevant alternatives (IIA) violations, where the relative preference between two given alternatives depends on the value of a third (distracter) alternative14; however, Gluth et al.15 conclude in a replication study that there is no effect of distracter value on choice behaviour in their dataset, instead finding an effect on reaction times. Here, we reanalyse the replication dataset, graciously made available by the authors, using econometric techniques specifically designed to test for the presence of divisive normalization in multi-alternative choice datasets; while we observe some differences between their data and the dataset originally reported by Louie et al.14, overall we find compelling evidence for a divisive normalization effect in choice in their dataset. This discrepancy arises primarily from unnecessarily restrictive assumptions used in previous analyses14,15, emphasizing the importance of deriving the analysis directly from the choice theory itself. In sensory processing, divisive normalization is a prevalent computation observed in multiple brain regions, sensory modalities, cognitive processes and species from invertebrates to humans1. Recent studies suggest that divisive normalization also plays a crucial role in the neural representation of subjective value, and consequently, choice behaviour. At the neural level, divisive normalization captures context-dependent value coding8,12, characterizes reward-related neural dynamics9 and falls within the class of provably optimal methods for encoding value under neural noise10. At the behavioural level, divisive normalization predicts both within-choice and across-choice context effects observed in nematodes4, monkeys13,14 and humans2,5–7,14. An early example of divisive normalization-predicted choice behaviour is a negative distracter effect in trinary choice, in which distracter value diminishes relative choice accuracy14. However, variable and even opposite distracter effects have also been observed2,3, emphasizing the importance of replication studies and robust tests for divisive normalization in behaviour. The Gluth et al.15 replication employed a three-alternative choice experiment that was analysed with a binary logit regression on the average valuations of each alternative V1, V2 and V3 in the choice set. This model was estimated both at the participant level (with random effects) and via a hierarchical analysis that allows each participant’s behaviour to arise from a distribution estimated at the level of the pooled sample. While a similar analysis approach was used by Louie et al.14, we have more recently noted that this method of analysis faces a number of challenges11:}
}

